And we did not have Red #40
3,000, 4,000, 10,000 years ago.

00:10:48.930 --> 00:10:51.900
So yes, you can eat too
much avocado or too much

00:10:51.900 --> 00:10:54.860
cashews or too many
things and gain weight.

00:10:54.860 --> 00:10:58.050
So, if you don't overeat,
you will not gain weight.

00:10:58.050 --> 00:11:00.720
Then we get into food quantity--
or sorry, food quality, which

00:11:00.720 --> 00:11:01.900
is what I just talked about.

00:11:01.900 --> 00:11:04.320
And I don't care if
you're paleo or vegan,

00:11:04.320 --> 00:11:06.840
nobody should be eating
hydrogenated fats.

00:11:06.840 --> 00:11:08.310
Nobody should be
eating pesticides.

00:11:08.310 --> 00:11:11.210
Nobody should be eating
growth hormones, and so on.

00:11:11.210 --> 00:11:13.170
Two universal rules.

00:11:13.170 --> 00:11:16.589
When I look at the rest of the
diets today, they really are--

00:11:16.589 --> 00:11:17.880
I look at them like a religion.

00:11:17.880 --> 00:11:20.640
We were talking
about it's choice.

00:11:20.640 --> 00:11:21.300
I'm Buddhist.

00:11:21.300 --> 00:11:22.420
Awesome.

00:11:22.420 --> 00:11:22.920
Great.

00:11:22.920 --> 00:11:23.580
I'm paleo.

00:11:23.580 --> 00:11:24.720
Fantastic.

00:11:24.720 --> 00:11:25.500
I'm vegan.

00:11:25.500 --> 00:11:26.670
Wonderful.

00:11:26.670 --> 00:11:31.950
So what I would simply say is
that if you choose a diet--

00:11:31.950 --> 00:11:33.870
and generally, they're
macronutrient ratios,

00:11:33.870 --> 00:11:35.260
if you think about it.

00:11:35.260 --> 00:11:37.710
So if you're choosing a diet
to be vegan, vegetarian,

00:11:37.710 --> 00:11:39.889
pescatarian,
omnivore, paleo, there

00:11:39.889 --> 00:11:41.430
are certain pitfalls
with every diet.

00:11:41.430 --> 00:11:45.030
As long as you're aware of
them and you're not overeating,

00:11:45.030 --> 00:11:47.010
and you're not eating
poor quality food,

00:11:47.010 --> 00:11:48.444
you'll be fine across the board.

00:11:48.444 --> 00:11:50.610
So with paleo, make sure
you're getting enough fiber

00:11:50.610 --> 00:11:51.840
and phytonutrients.

00:11:51.840 --> 00:11:53.984
Make sure the meat
you're eating is organic.

00:11:53.984 --> 00:11:56.400
I mean, we can get into the
environmental aspects of that,

00:11:56.400 --> 00:11:58.050
but that's not really
the conversation.

00:11:58.050 --> 00:12:00.390
If you're vegan,
and you're a woman--

00:12:00.390 --> 00:12:05.445
men do much better on vegan
diets, because they don't--

00:12:05.445 --> 00:12:06.300
how do you say--

00:12:06.300 --> 00:12:07.260
MARY LIZ MCCURDY: Menstruate?

00:12:07.260 --> 00:12:08.676
JILLIAN MICHAELS:
Thanks for that.

00:12:08.676 --> 00:12:10.410
That.

00:12:10.410 --> 00:12:11.902
Appreciate you.

00:12:11.902 --> 00:12:15.141
I'm like a five-year-old
with shit like that.

00:12:15.141 --> 00:12:18.581
I'm like, you know,
that thing that happens.

00:12:18.581 --> 00:12:19.080
Right.

00:12:19.080 --> 00:12:21.452
So men do much better on vegan
diets, believe it or not,

00:12:21.452 --> 00:12:23.160
because they actually
have too much iron.

00:12:23.160 --> 00:12:25.500
But we lose iron every month,
so we're more-- females

00:12:25.500 --> 00:12:27.270
are more prone to anemia.

00:12:27.270 --> 00:12:30.120
As long as you're
getting B12, a B12 shot,

00:12:30.120 --> 00:12:34.840
and good sources of iron in
your diet, you'll be fine.

00:12:34.840 --> 00:12:37.895
And if there are allergies,
like gluten allergies, then,

00:12:37.895 --> 00:12:40.020
of course, you'll know what
your sensitivities are,

00:12:40.020 --> 00:12:41.894
if you're lactose
intolerant, and then you'll

00:12:41.894 --> 00:12:43.230
just avoid those things.

00:12:43.230 --> 00:12:45.510
When it comes to
fine-tuning macronutrients,

00:12:45.510 --> 00:12:47.790
I would simply say
listen to your body.

00:12:47.790 --> 00:12:50.250
And this is where,
because people do

00:12:50.250 --> 00:12:55.106
convert food into glucose
at faster or slower paces--

00:12:55.106 --> 00:12:56.730
I wrote a book about
it many years ago,

00:12:56.730 --> 00:12:57.810
and it was based on--

00:12:57.810 --> 00:12:59.920
it's called oxidizer types.

00:12:59.920 --> 00:13:04.560
So, the way you can tell, quite
honestly, is if you eat a meal

00:13:04.560 --> 00:13:08.340
and it's predominately fat and
protein, and you feel superb,

00:13:08.340 --> 00:13:11.640
then you likely break
down your food very quick,

00:13:11.640 --> 00:13:15.160
because those things
break down very slowly.

00:13:15.160 --> 00:13:19.960
Now, if you eat whole grain
toast and a little bit of fruit

00:13:19.960 --> 00:13:22.170
spread on top, and
you're like, oh my God,

00:13:22.170 --> 00:13:23.504
I'm exhausted, same thing.

00:13:23.504 --> 00:13:25.170
So that's a person
that breaks down food

00:13:25.170 --> 00:13:27.284
more quickly, in
which case, if you

00:13:27.284 --> 00:13:28.950
eat things that break
down more quickly,

00:13:28.950 --> 00:13:30.990
you're going to spike and crash.

00:13:30.990 --> 00:13:33.710
Whereas, conversely, if you
break things down more slowly,

00:13:33.710 --> 00:13:35.250
and you eat a ton
of fat and protein

00:13:35.250 --> 00:13:38.670
and you feel like you've got a
weight sitting in your stomach

00:13:38.670 --> 00:13:40.440
and you feel lethargic,
you'll do better

00:13:40.440 --> 00:13:43.390
with more complex carbohydrates.

00:13:43.390 --> 00:13:45.690
So that's where I would just
say listen to your body.

00:13:45.690 --> 00:13:48.697
And the whole idea is really
how much energy do you have?

00:13:48.697 --> 00:13:49.780
That's what will tell you.

00:13:49.780 --> 00:13:52.080
And how long do
you feel satiated?

00:13:52.080 --> 00:13:55.004
So, if you feel satiated
for three to four hours

00:13:55.004 --> 00:13:57.420
and you feel like you can keep
going without eating again,

00:13:57.420 --> 00:13:58.650
you've stabilized
your blood sugar

00:13:58.650 --> 00:13:59.983
and you've hit that right ratio.

00:13:59.983 --> 00:14:02.379
And a great place to
start is just be balanced.

00:14:02.379 --> 00:14:04.170
South-- that's why
South Beach did so well.

00:14:04.170 --> 00:14:05.340
It's 30, 30, 40.

00:14:05.340 --> 00:14:06.450
Start there.

00:14:06.450 --> 00:14:08.280
And if you feel great,
don't fuck with it.

00:14:08.280 --> 00:14:09.960
If you don't, tweak
it a little bit

00:14:09.960 --> 00:14:11.463
and see what gives
you more energy.

00:14:11.463 --> 00:14:12.504
MARY LIZ MCCURDY: Mm-hmm.

00:14:12.504 --> 00:14:13.430
Awesome.

00:14:13.430 --> 00:14:14.860
So going back to the--

00:14:14.860 --> 00:14:18.330
super helpful hearing a little
bit about the navigating diet

00:14:18.330 --> 00:14:21.490
trends, one thing that's come
up recently in the press,

00:14:21.490 --> 00:14:22.990
or maybe, you know,
you've seen this

00:14:22.990 --> 00:14:25.720
in the past couple of
years, is New York Times'

00:14:25.720 --> 00:14:29.945
deep dives on the role genetics
is playing on your metabolism.

00:14:29.945 --> 00:14:31.570
And they've done some
interesting work,

00:14:31.570 --> 00:14:33.730
like looking at the
Biggest Loser contestants

00:14:33.730 --> 00:14:34.700
before and after.

00:14:34.700 --> 00:14:35.850
JILLIAN MICHAELS: That's an
interesting conversation.

00:14:35.850 --> 00:14:36.460
MARY LIZ MCCURDY: Yeah.

00:14:36.460 --> 00:14:38.665
So I would love to hear
about your thoughts on,

00:14:38.665 --> 00:14:40.430
you know, is it
nature or nurture?

00:14:40.430 --> 00:14:42.790
Are we-- is it like baby,
I was born this way, or--

00:14:42.790 --> 00:14:42.920
JILLIAN MICHAELS: Right.

00:14:42.920 --> 00:14:43.120
MARY LIZ MCCURDY:
--is there actually

00:14:43.120 --> 00:14:44.328
something we can do about it?

00:14:44.328 --> 00:14:45.220
JILLIAN MICHAELS: OK.

00:14:45.220 --> 00:14:47.330
Well, we'll get to "Biggest
Loser" in a minute.

00:14:47.330 --> 00:14:49.720
First, let's discuss genetics.

00:14:49.720 --> 00:14:51.820
Your genetics are as
unique on the inside

00:14:51.820 --> 00:14:53.570
as they are on the
outside, right,

00:14:53.570 --> 00:14:56.440
and for evolutionary purposes.

00:14:56.440 --> 00:15:00.047
With that said, how you
respond to certain foods,

00:15:00.047 --> 00:15:01.630
right, we were talking
about-- will be

00:15:01.630 --> 00:15:03.412
different for differing people.

00:15:03.412 --> 00:15:04.870
Some people are
lactose intolerant.

00:15:04.870 --> 00:15:06.700
Some have gluten sensitivities.

00:15:06.700 --> 00:15:10.000
Some people, as we
look at micronutrients,

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:12.250
some people will respond
to them in positive ways,

00:15:12.250 --> 00:15:14.680
and some people it
won't do anything for.

00:15:14.680 --> 00:15:19.240
But if you're looking at
weight, everybody can be fit.

00:15:19.240 --> 00:15:21.130
Now, are you-- is
everybody going

00:15:21.130 --> 00:15:23.140
to be a size zero
with, you know,

00:15:23.140 --> 00:15:25.180
this percentage of body fat?

00:15:25.180 --> 00:15:25.930
No.

00:15:25.930 --> 00:15:26.180
Right?

00:15:26.180 --> 00:15:28.540
That-- that's going to
involve your unique genetics.

00:15:28.540 --> 00:15:30.250
Can anybody be fit and healthy?

00:15:30.250 --> 00:15:31.090
Yes.

00:15:31.090 --> 00:15:32.840
Is it easier for
some than others?

00:15:32.840 --> 00:15:33.340
Yes.

00:15:33.340 --> 00:15:37.240
I mean, if I look at
food, I will gain weight.

00:15:37.240 --> 00:15:38.290
I was an overweight kid.

00:15:38.290 --> 00:15:40.720
I mean, I cannot play
those kinds of games.

00:15:40.720 --> 00:15:41.500
I just can't.

00:15:41.500 --> 00:15:43.780
It's not-- like, you know,
my partner can eat anything

00:15:43.780 --> 00:15:45.865
she wants, and is
still like, ugh,

00:15:45.865 --> 00:15:47.680
I'm just trying to put
on five more pounds.

00:15:51.400 --> 00:15:53.577
You know, I mean, and
that's-- and that's genetics.

00:15:53.577 --> 00:15:54.910
But are we both fit and healthy?

00:15:54.910 --> 00:15:55.660
Yes.

00:15:55.660 --> 00:15:59.920
So, you can dramatically affect
the expression of your genetics

00:15:59.920 --> 00:16:00.850
for better or worse.

00:16:00.850 --> 00:16:03.400
So nutrigenomics, how does
food express your genetics,

00:16:03.400 --> 00:16:04.240
epigenetics.

00:16:04.240 --> 00:16:06.880
How's your environment
expressing--

00:16:06.880 --> 00:16:09.100
facilitating the expression
of your genetics?

00:16:09.100 --> 00:16:11.650
So, we are all
empowered, for better

00:16:11.650 --> 00:16:17.200
and for worse, which brings
me to "Biggest Loser."

00:16:17.200 --> 00:16:18.800
And it's kind of interesting.

00:16:18.800 --> 00:16:22.682
So, one of those
contestants is a girl

00:16:22.682 --> 00:16:25.140
named Shay, who is one of the
biggest contestants we'd ever

00:16:25.140 --> 00:16:25.960
had on the show.

00:16:25.960 --> 00:16:30.690
She's-- was over 500 pounds, and
she's still a friend of mine.

00:16:30.690 --> 00:16:32.760
And, you know, they
put the weight back on.

00:16:32.760 --> 00:16:34.680
And if they don't
ask for help, I

00:16:34.680 --> 00:16:36.880
don't give unsolicited advice.

00:16:36.880 --> 00:16:38.887
So I was like,
whatever, we're friends,

00:16:38.887 --> 00:16:40.470
I'm not going to say
a word unless she

00:16:40.470 --> 00:16:41.344
talks to me about it.

00:16:41.344 --> 00:16:44.280
This is also a woman-- and a lot
of those people on that show,

00:16:44.280 --> 00:16:46.170
you have to understand--

00:16:46.170 --> 00:16:47.940
people watched it,
and it was a TV show,

00:16:47.940 --> 00:16:51.270
but, for me, it was a
life-or-death intervention

00:16:51.270 --> 00:16:52.740
on a ticking clock.

00:16:52.740 --> 00:16:54.990
And you're dealing with trauma.

00:16:54.990 --> 00:16:56.220
Tremendous trauma.

00:16:56.220 --> 00:17:00.990
People don't get to 400, 500
pounds without deep trauma.

00:17:00.990 --> 00:17:02.700
It's not because
they like pizza.

00:17:02.700 --> 00:17:03.240
It's not.

00:17:03.240 --> 00:17:05.550
I love pizza; I'm
not 500 pounds.

00:17:05.550 --> 00:17:08.107
So, this is a
woman whose parents

00:17:08.107 --> 00:17:10.440
were drug addicts, who was
in and out of the foster care

00:17:10.440 --> 00:17:12.510
system.

00:17:12.510 --> 00:17:14.099
So the study comes
out, and she's

00:17:14.099 --> 00:17:15.400
like, I'm just curious
what you think?

00:17:15.400 --> 00:17:16.510
I saw you said it was bullshit.

00:17:16.510 --> 00:17:18.450
I'm like, you know I
think it's bullshit, Shay.

00:17:18.450 --> 00:17:19.210
And she's like, why?

00:17:19.210 --> 00:17:20.626
And I was like,
tell me right now,

00:17:20.626 --> 00:17:22.890
are you eating 2000
calories a day?

00:17:22.890 --> 00:17:23.579
No.

00:17:23.579 --> 00:17:25.930
Are you moving your body
for four half hours a week?

00:17:25.930 --> 00:17:26.430
No.

00:17:26.430 --> 00:17:28.890
I was like, try that
and get back to me.

00:17:28.890 --> 00:17:31.800
She lost 85 pounds,
again, in six months,

00:17:31.800 --> 00:17:34.455
eating 2000 calories a day and
walking four half hours a week.

00:17:34.455 --> 00:17:37.246
Got diagnosed with
thyroid cancer.

00:17:37.246 --> 00:17:39.870
Just got it out, and she's-- we
don't even know if she's cancer

00:17:39.870 --> 00:17:42.060
free yet, so that was kind
of a bump in the road.

00:17:42.060 --> 00:17:43.530
But she's now maintained.

00:17:43.530 --> 00:17:45.840
So she's like 425 again.

00:17:45.840 --> 00:17:49.380
So it's like the minute we put
her back on 2000 calories a day

00:17:49.380 --> 00:17:51.990
and walking four
half hours a week,

00:17:51.990 --> 00:17:55.000
85 pounds falls off of her.

00:17:55.000 --> 00:17:57.650
This is-- you know, and have
to understand the psychology.

00:17:57.650 --> 00:17:59.900
There's a lot of shame that
goes on, so it's like, no,

00:17:59.900 --> 00:18:00.835
the show did it.

00:18:00.835 --> 00:18:03.460
And when they were on the show,
it was, mommy and daddy did it.

00:18:03.460 --> 00:18:06.610
And when-- what you really
need in that scenario

00:18:06.610 --> 00:18:10.450
is a therapist, because when
you're eating like that,

00:18:10.450 --> 00:18:12.280
there's much deeper
stuff going on.

00:18:12.280 --> 00:18:17.410
And people don't eat
dangerously or engage

00:18:17.410 --> 00:18:20.260
in destructive behaviors because
they're weak or they're stupid

00:18:20.260 --> 00:18:21.830
or they're lazy.

00:18:21.830 --> 00:18:23.080
It's affording them something.

00:18:23.080 --> 00:18:25.360
And it's affording them
something very significant.

00:18:25.360 --> 00:18:28.270
And at one time or another,
that destructive habit

00:18:28.270 --> 00:18:30.860
meant their
psychological survival.

00:18:30.860 --> 00:18:33.130
So whether it was a
connection to a loved one,

00:18:33.130 --> 00:18:35.860
or control, or
protection, you won't know

00:18:35.860 --> 00:18:37.750
until you deal with the person.

00:18:37.750 --> 00:18:42.310
But, to give that up is
way deeper than anything

00:18:42.310 --> 00:18:44.320
we can comprehend
on the surface.

00:18:44.320 --> 00:18:46.700
And that's-- that's what
that animal's really about.

00:18:46.700 --> 00:18:47.412
MARY LIZ MCCURDY: Got it.

00:18:47.412 --> 00:18:49.060
JILLIAN MICHAELS: It's
not about food at all.

00:18:49.060 --> 00:18:49.570
MARY LIZ MCCURDY: Yeah.

00:18:49.570 --> 00:18:51.550
JILLIAN MICHAELS: Well,
it is, but not literally.

00:18:51.550 --> 00:18:52.591
MARY LIZ MCCURDY: Mm-hmm.

00:18:52.591 --> 00:18:55.250
That's a helpful insight.

